Lokales Engagement als Gegenmittel gegen den Populismus
PARIS – Die einst die westlichen Demokratien dominienden Parteien wurden in ihrem Kern erschüttert.
Viele – u. a. in Frankreich, Italien, Griechenland und im Vereinigten Königreich – haben krachende Wahlniederlagen erlitten.
Andere haben sich so drastisch verändert, dass nur noch der Name geblieben ist.
Die Republikanische Partei von US-Präsident Donald Trump hat mit der des früheren Präsidenten Ronald Reagan kaum noch etwas gemein.
Diese Entwicklungen ähneln sich überall im Westen.
Die Führungen der einstmals dominanten Parteien schwanken zwischen Verleugnung und Verzweiflung hin und her, während Populisten ihre traditionellen Anhänger abfischen.
Einige weigern sich, einen legitimen Grund für ihre Niederlage zu erkennen, und tun ihre Unterstützer ihrer Gegner als „bedauernswert“ ab, so wie Hillary Clinton es tat, kurz bevor sie 2016 gegen Trump verlor; andere sind angesichts der populistischen Flut zu verschreckt, um eine Gegenoffensive zu starten.
Doch werden weder Verleugnung noch Selbstzufriedenheit die festgefahrene politische Situation auflösen.
Die Progressiven müssen sich neu aufstellen, und das beginnt mit einer Diagnose der Unzulänglichkeiten der traditionellen Parteien.
Apart of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the true issues of our time.
Captivated still by the old ideological battlefields, they ignored declining social mobility, intensifying environmental crises, increasing geographic inequality, tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other topics that truly matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were at the forefront.
Now they stand alone in the forest, wondering where everyone else went.
The social sciences might be ready with an answer as to why the mainstream has veered off course.
The gap between their objective analysis of reality and government policy has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the increasing disparity in income and other indicators between some prosperous, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
Yet, before French President Emmanuel Macron's government did so, no national government chief had implemented tax cuts based on place of residence.
As a result of this policy, now 1% of French GDP is primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
The traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters instead of only through the filters of media and opinion polls.
In 2016, Macron launched his movement En Marche! with the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the interviewers then became the basis of Macron's presidential election campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct, and Macron promised to address the issue if elected.
At the time, his stance made him a target of jokes for his opponents; however, their laughter quickly faded with the emergence of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
The traditional parties suffer from poor organization as well.
They long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and candidates cheer each other on.
This was less about cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to seize and hold power.
It is no wonder that citizens, and even party members, feel ignored between elections.
Trotz dieser Schwächen hatten die etablierten Parteien eine Anzahl von Vorteilen, die ihren Zusammenbruch hinauszögerten.
In den letzten Jahren hatten sie einen technologischen Vorsprung gegenüber weniger etablierten Gegnern, und sie waren die einzigen politischen Akteure mit organisierten Wählergruppen, die die Menschen zu den Wahlen mobilisieren, Proteste organisieren und Petitionen starten konnten.
Aber dieses Modell trägt nicht mehr.
Die Bürger weigern sich heutzutag
Zusammen mit einem höheren Bildungsniveau kamen neue Forderungen nach Teilhabe.
The voters want to be treated as political actors with rights of their own, not as pawns in someone else's game.
Moreover, governments are no longer the sole providers of political measures.
This is one of the hard lessons we learned during the two years we worked alongside Macron in the Élysée Palace.
The most pressing political challenges today—climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality—cannot be addressed by national governments alone.
These challenges require deep cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at both subnational and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to political participation, so traditional parties can no longer rely on the frontrunner bonus and entrenched supporter networks.
Whoever knows how to use Google, Twitter, and Facebook doesn't need an old party apparatus that spans centuries.
Political movements need to be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures rather than just elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "backoffice"; the front office should be staffed with people on the ground.
Bei La République En Marche! bezeichnen wir dies als lokale Bürgerprojekte.
Diese können von Lesekursen nach der Schule und Integrationsprogrammen für Einwanderer bis hin zu genossenschaftlichen Gemüsegärten und digitalen Schulungen für Senioren reichen.
In jedem Fall geht es darum, auf lokale Probleme zugeschnittene Lösungen anzubieten und auf diese Weise die Gemeinwesen zu stärken.
Man sollte derartige Projekte heute als unverzichtbare Ergänzungen staatlicher Politik betrachten.
In Zukunft wird die Fähigkeit einer Partei, lohnende Wege für politisches und kommunales Engagement anzubieten, für ihre Attraktivität wesentlich sein.
And by demonstrating their reform policies daily "live," the parties have already laid the groundwork for success at the ballot box.
If voters refuse to listen to what needs to be said, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson the traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, not just winning elections, can win over the people.
Reconnecting with the concerns of voters therefore goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need a progressive policy on the ground.
